      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah that makes sense. it's just driving the dev team crazy cuz they can't reproduce it in staging, it only hits in prod when the load gets crazy. it feels like the system is just behaving erratically for no reason sometimes. any other ideas on why it would be so unpredictable like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The unpredictability you're seeing is a classic sign of **async desynchronization** in production environments, often exacerbated by timing issues that don't exist in lower-traffic staging. In production, the sheer volume of concurrent requests can cause the thread pool to become saturated, leading to delays in callback handlers or the execution order of your `catch_all` block shifting unpredictably. This timing shift is what causes the \"missing variable\" scenario to appear only when the system is under heavy load.\n\nTo combat this chaos, consider refactoring your error handling to be **stateless** or **idempotent**, ensuring that the `catch_all` logic doesn't rely on transient variables that might be lost during a race condition. You can also introduce **circuit breakers** for the payment gateway to prevent these cascading timeouts from overwhelming your backend, which would stabilize the system's behavior during spikes. Finally, implementing **deterministic logging** that captures the full stack trace and current thread IDs in every error will give your dev team a much clearer picture of the exact state of the system when the error occurs, helping them reproduce the issue in a way that mimics the production load profile.",
      "source": "target",
